<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-833-972  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 833 972.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Oct 1989 v62 n10 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Price tag for faulty nets: $3.5 million.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Partial disabilities in large networks cost $3.5 million in lostproductivity annually and $600,000 annually in lost revenue, astudy by Infonetics Inc indicates.andP;  A partial disability is onethat impairs but does not halt performance.andP;  A telephone survey of100 Fortune 500 companies with networks averaging 320 nodesreveals an average 24 disabilities per year, with averagedisability time of 4.8 hours.andP;  Companies in the survey spend anaverage $670,000 annually solving disability problems but thefunds are often spent unwisely, according to Harry Saal, presidentof Network General Corp, which funded the study.andP;  Saal says thestudy highlights the need for network analyzers.andP;  Differentvendors' analyzers are effective in different trouble spots.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Infonetics Inc. (reports)Network General Corp. (reports).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksReliabilityCostUser Survey.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   What causes network problems? (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>